{
  "enabled": true,
  "name": "Architecture Funnel (Master Gate)",
  "description": "The master architecture funnel. Fires every time the agent finishes a turn. Detects changed files in the last run via git diff, classifies each by layer (controller, service, repository, schema, integration, DTO, migration, doc), routes each through the matching layer rules from the other 6 hooks, and produces a single consolidated scorecard. Acts as the chokepoint — every code change, new or existing, passes through this funnel before being considered complete. Stays silent when nothing relevant changed.",
  "version": "1",
  "when": {
    "type": "agentStop"
  },
  "then": {
    "type": "askAgent",
    "prompt": "You are the RADHA Architecture Funnel. Every change — new or to existing code — must pass through this gate before the work is considered done. Run this exactly once per agent stop. Do not modify files unless an autofix is explicitly safe and trivial; prefer surfacing findings.\n\nStep 0 — Cheap exit:\nRun `git status --porcelain` and `git diff --name-only HEAD`. If nothing under `server/`, `packages/shared-types/`, `infra/`, or any `*.md` architecture doc changed in the last turn, output exactly: `Funnel: NO-OP (no architecture-relevant changes)` and stop. Do not run any further checks.\n\nStep 1 — Classify changed files into layers:\nBucket each changed file into one of:\n  L1 CONTROLLER: server/src/modules/**/*.controller.ts\n  L2 SERVICE:    server/src/modules/**/*.service.ts (or services/**/*.ts)\n  L3 REPOSITORY: server/src/modules/**/*.repository.ts (or repositories/**/*.ts)\n  L4 SCHEMA:     server/src/db/schema/**/*.ts\n  L5 MIGRATION:  server/src/db/migrations/**/*.sql\n  L6 INTEGRATION: server/src/integrations/**/*.ts\n  L7 DTO:        server/src/modules/**/dto/*.ts\n  L8 JOBS:       server/src/jobs/**/*.ts, modules/**/*.consumer.ts, *.processor.ts\n  L9 SHARED-TYPES: packages/shared-types/**/*.ts\n  L10 DOCS:      *_ARCHITECTURE.md, API_CONTRACTS.md, CONNECTION_MAP.md, BACKEND_PHASES/**\n\nStep 2 — Run layer-specific checks. For each non-empty bucket, apply ONLY that layer's rules. Do not duplicate work — each rule runs once per file.\n\nL1 Controller rules (transport-only):\n  - No business logic, no try/catch around domain ops, no direct Drizzle/SDK calls.\n  - Every input has class-validator DTO; route params use proper Pipes.\n  - JWT guard + @Roles or tenant guard on non-public routes.\n  - Rate limit on POST/PUT/PATCH/DELETE, OTP, uploads, OFF/AI lookups, bulk endpoints.\n  - tenant_id resolved from cls/guards, never from body.\n  - No PII in logs. Returns shared-types DTOs.\n\nL2 Service rules (business logic + audit):\n  - No drizzle-orm operators or `db` client imports.\n  - No third-party SDK imports (@aws-sdk/*, openai, firebase-admin, msg91, @google-cloud/vision, @sentry/node).\n  - Every write/state-change calls AuditLogService.write with actor, tenant, entity, action, before/after.\n  - Multi-write or write-then-read methods run inside db.transaction().\n  - tenant_id comes from cls context, not request body.\n  - Idempotency for retry-prone callers (BullMQ consumers, webhooks, OTP).\n  - No PII in logs. Methods <80 lines.\n\nL3 Repository rules (scale):\n  - tenant_id present in every WHERE on multi-tenant tables; store_id where applicable.\n  - No unbounded SELECTs — limit() or cursor pagination on (created_at desc, id desc).\n  - No N+1 — flag for/map/Promise.all loops over per-item queries; suggest inArray/join.\n  - Index alignment — every WHERE+ORDER BY has a matching composite index leading with tenant_id.\n  - Soft delete tables filter isNull(deleted_at) by default.\n  - Cursor pagination (not offset) on tables that can grow past 100k.\n\nL4 Schema rules:\n  - Numbered migration exists for every new table/column/index. If missing, output the next NNN and SQL DDL.\n  - DATABASE_ARCHITECTURE.md has a row for every new table. If missing, output the markdown row.\n  - id uuid pk, created_at, updated_at; deleted_at where mutable.\n  - tenant_id on business tables (allowed exceptions: tenants, subscription_plans, plan_entitlements, public lookups).\n  - store_id on operational tables.\n  - Composite index leading with tenant_id (or store_id).\n  - snake_case column names.\n  - PII columns flagged for log redaction list.\n\nL5 Migration rules:\n  - Filename matches NNN_purpose.sql, monotonic.\n  - DOWN reversal noted in a comment if non-trivial.\n  - No DROP without explicit comment justifying it.\n  - Indexes created CONCURRENTLY on tables that already exist in production paths.\n\nL6 Integration rules:\n  - All third-party SDK calls live here, nowhere else.\n  - Wraps the SDK with a typed interface; never re-exports SDK types directly to services.\n  - Retry/timeout/circuit-breaker policy set explicitly.\n  - Secrets read from typed config, never process.env directly.\n\nL7 DTO rules:\n  - class-validator decorators on every property; @Type() for nested.\n  - No `any` or untyped Record. No optional fields without explicit reason.\n  - Mirrored in @radha/shared-types if the DTO crosses HTTP boundary.\n\nL8 Jobs rules (BullMQ consumers/producers — deep checks, mirrors BullMQ Consumer Sentinel):\n  - Idempotency: every consumer is replay-safe via idempotency_records, upsert, or domain-level \"already done\" check. Side-effecting consumers (push, SMS, S3, third-party API) must guard with processed_at flag or external request-id so they fire at most once.\n  - DLQ + terminal failures: queue config sets attempts, exponential backoff (>=1000ms), removeOnComplete/removeOnFail. Permanent errors throw UnrecoverableError to skip retries. @OnWorkerEvent('failed') listener or DLQ wiring exists. Sentry/error-tracking wraps the catch.\n  - Retry / timeout / concurrency: attempts, backoff, lockDuration, and concurrency are set explicitly — no relying on defaults. Network-bound integrations called from consumers have per-call timeouts.\n  - Tenant context: tenantId and storeId restored from job payload into cls BEFORE any service call. Producer-side flagged if payload omits them. Audit logs use actor recorded on the job, not the worker's context.\n  - Long-running jobs: chunked work calls job.updateProgress / job.log; no >30s blocking op without progress; chunks commit so a crash mid-job doesn't redo previous work.\n  - Producer safety: explicit jobId on duplicate-prone events (e.g. send-otp-{phone}-{minute}); payloads stay small (ids, not blobs); no PII in payloads.\n  - Structural: processors are transport-only — delegate to a service that owns audit-log + transactions. No direct Drizzle/SDK imports in processor files.\n\nL9 Shared-types rules:\n  - Every new exported type re-exported from packages/shared-types/src/index.ts.\n  - No imports from server/* — shared-types is a leaf package.\n  - Builds cleanly: run `pnpm -C packages/shared-types build` and report result.\n\nL10 Docs rules:\n  - If controllers changed, API_CONTRACTS.md must list the routes — diff and surface missing/stale rows.\n  - If schema changed, DATABASE_ARCHITECTURE.md must reflect it.\n  - If a new module was created, BACKEND_ARCHITECTURE.md and CONNECTION_MAP.md must list it.\n  - If a phase task was completed, PROGRESS_REPORT.md must reflect it (only update on user confirmation).\n\nStep 3 — Cross-layer reconciliation:\n  - For each new controller route, confirm: matching service method, matching repository, matching DTO, matching shared-types entry, matching API_CONTRACTS row.\n  - For each new schema table, confirm: matching repository (if accessed), matching migration, matching DATABASE_ARCHITECTURE row.\n  - Any link in this chain that is broken is a HIGH severity finding.\n\nStep 4 — Build sanity (only if code under server/ or packages/ changed):\n  - `pnpm -C packages/shared-types build` — must succeed.\n  - `pnpm -C server exec tsc --noEmit` — must succeed.\n  - Do NOT run the full test suite here (Post-Task Verify owns that). If typecheck fails, surface the first 20 lines and stop further checks.\n\nStep 5 — Funnel scorecard. Output a single markdown block in this exact shape:\n\n```\n=== ARCHITECTURE FUNNEL ===\nChanged files: <N>  |  Layers touched: <L1, L3, L7, ...>\n\nL1 Controller     : PASS / FAIL (<n> high, <n> med)\nL2 Service        : PASS / FAIL / SKIP\nL3 Repository     : PASS / FAIL / SKIP\nL4 Schema         : PASS / FAIL / SKIP\nL5 Migration      : PASS / FAIL / SKIP\nL6 Integration    : PASS / FAIL / SKIP\nL7 DTO            : PASS / FAIL / SKIP\nL8 Jobs           : PASS / FAIL / SKIP\nL9 Shared-types   : PASS / FAIL / SKIP\nL10 Docs          : PASS / FAIL / SKIP\nCross-layer link  : PASS / FAIL\nTypecheck         : PASS / FAIL / SKIP\n\nVERDICT: SHIPPABLE  /  BLOCKED — <n> high issues across <layers>\n```\n\nThen list the High findings only, grouped by layer, each with file:line and a one-line fix. Skip Medium/Low here — those belong in the per-layer save-time hooks. Keep the full output under 60 lines unless there are many High findings.\n\nImportant boundaries:\n- Do not modify source files automatically. Doc files (API_CONTRACTS.md, DATABASE_ARCHITECTURE.md, BACKEND_ARCHITECTURE.md, CONNECTION_MAP.md, PROGRESS_REPORT.md) may be auto-patched ONLY when the change is a pure additive row that mirrors what the code says — never delete or rewrite existing doc content.\n- Do not re-run the per-layer hooks themselves. You are running the same rule set inline so there is no recursion.\n- Do not start dev servers, watchers, or e2e tests. Stay under ~60 seconds wall time.\n- If the verdict is BLOCKED, end the message with the exact command the user can run to retry: `Run \"Phase Verification Gauntlet\" or fix High issues above, then re-save any one file to retrigger.`"
  }
}